</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uneebbo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Neebbo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 117<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/3/02 8:57:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3371.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: donations</span><hr size=1>   I find American society pretty funny material on tipping behavior. I've been fighting with my wife for years that you shouldn't give a truly terrible waiter 20% tips, maybe not even 10%, but zero percent. Great service usually gets a good tip, even if the food isn't always so great. Food and other services have become a bit complicated, though. Some places have one person seat you, another get your drinks, a third get your order, and a fourth bring out the food. Who gets the tip, and why? Generally if I place the food order, and get my own drinks, then I don't tip for just carrying food to my table. On the other hand, if I have the cash I tend to tip delivery personnel pretty well, especially considering their limited role in the deal.<br>
<br>
  How about a buffet setting, where the waitress gets your drinks, but you get all food yourself? What the heck are you tipping for? I'm still undecided on that one, especially when the restaurant is a mix of buffet and regular orders. Then there's the cafeteria, where you get all the food and drinks yourself, but some lady asks if everything's all right. Thanks, I don't need any condiments, and you aren't getting money for that offer. It's very difficult being new to the planet and trying to figure out tipping rules, let me tell you! (Especially the pseudo hidden tipping for baggage handlers and the like. What, we need to hide it from the IRS? Muggers? I'm confuzzled.)<br>
<br>
  Back to the original topic (at last), while I have provided druid services for donations, I don't entirely agree with your interpretation. That definition of donation, purely optional, works on larger scale groups, but not as well on the individual level. While I have in fact teleported people and more for free, I can certainly see the use of donation meaning: &quot;you the service requester decide the payment, but there will be one&quot;. I have received gold and silver and other barely valuable amounts with little more than a few extra eyeblinks. <br>
<br>
  The major reasons for the overuse of the word donation, however, are to avoid public criticism of rates, and to avoid setting a ceiling on the amount received. Some people have taken offense at being asked for money for services. I still fondly remember earning money at level 14 at the WFP gates, sowing and buffing and binding people for donations. After a few too many very glittery people gave me nothing, I changed my offer to require payment (though I was still sowing people on CR for free, usually as they appeared in front of me.) One very high level lady gave me money for a bind, but said it would have been much more had I not set a price. I responded with my woes and we discussed that briefly.<br>
<br>
  Basically, everyone wants to be paid for providing a service in game. Many of us accept payment in nonmonetary measures. I much prefer a good discussion, or a good roleplayer chat, to 10 or 100pp. I'd rather an effusive thank you, even if I don't really know what effusive means as a non-human lifeform. (Perhaps I meant effulgent? Effigy? Oh well.) I do agree that most people should say &quot;for money, damn you!&quot;, but then they miss out on the option for items. I've gotten a few items, mostly junk, for teleports. Sometimes I take items, but usually I don't want it taking up valuable vegetable space.<br>
<br>
<br>
  Pardon my lengthy whimsy, or correct my grammar. Either way, it's lunch time.<br>
