<br>
  That's nice, but that's not really my problem. (Also, it's Neebbo, two bs, dang it.) It's not stealing for me to withhold money when there was no agreement between me and waiter type that there would be a tip. It might be an implied situation that &quot;any reasonable&quot; person would leave a tip, but there's no set amount or even percentage. (One exception being those restaurants that print on their menus about gratuities added to large parties, but then it's forced onto the bill.)<br>
<br>
  Room service is another good one. I forget where I stayed a while back, but they added a tip to the bill, but left a place where you could increase the tip. Fine, but he's got his 15% and you think I should add more? Maybe if I were the demanding type and wanted unusual condiments or sent him back for things, I'd consider it. Wheeling a cart and moving a few dishes around doesn't sound like enough work to me.<br>
<br>
  Lest I sound like a total skinflint, I've been known to overtip for very entertaining, nice, or attentive waiters. On cheaper meals I've tipped more than the meal(s) cost a few times. I donated fairly well at a recent Rennaisance Festival for the two performances I liked a lot, even though both shows admitted to receiving pay already. With a hundred people per show, I was certainly under less pressure to donate.<br>
